  "description": "Trochee is a metrical foot consisting of a stressed syllable followed by an unstressed syllable: DUM-da. \u0026ldquo;GAR-den,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;NE-ver,\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;FALL-ing.\u0026rdquo; The trochee is the iamb\u0026rsquo;s mirror image — where the iamb rises, the trochee falls.\nTrochaic meter gives verse a driving, incantatory quality. Longfellow\u0026rsquo;s The Song of Hiawatha (\u0026ldquo;BY the SHORES of GIT-che GU-mee\u0026rdquo;) is the best-known sustained trochaic poem in English. The falling rhythm can feel insistent, chant-like, or ominous — Shakespeare\u0026rsquo;s witches in Macbeth speak in trochaic tetrameter (\u0026ldquo;DOU-ble, DOU-ble, TOIL and TROU-ble\u0026rdquo;) to set their speech apart from the play\u0026rsquo;s iambic norm.\n",
